\viewkind4\uc1\pard\qc\lang1033\i\f0\fs28 The Last Question\par
\pard\par
\pard\qj\tx204\i0\fs22 The last question was asked for the first time, half in jest, on May\par
21, 2061, at a time when humanity first stepped into the light.\par
The question came about as a result of a five-dollar bet over high-\par
balls, and it happened this way:\par
\pard\fi192\sl-238\slmult0\qj\tx192\f1 Alexander Adell and Bertram Lupov were two of the faithful attendants of Multivac. As well as any human beings could, they knew what lay behind the cold, clicking, flashing face\emdash miles and miles of face\emdash of that giant computer. They had at least a vague notion of the general plan of relays and circuits that had long since grown past the point where any single human could possibly have a firm grasp of the whole.\f0\par
\f1 Multivac was self-adjusting and self-correcting. It had to be, for nothing human could adjust and correct it quickly enough or even adequately enough. \emdash So Adell and Lupov attended the monstrous giant only lightly and superficially, yet as well as any men could. They fed it data, adjusted questions to its needs and translated the answers that were issued. Certainly they, and all others like them, were fully entitled to share in the glory that was Multivac\rquote s.\f0\par
For decades, Multivac had helped design the ships and plot the trajectories that enabled man to reach the Moon, Mars, \fs20 and \f1\fs22 Venus, but past that, Earth\rquote s poor resources could not support the ships. Too much energy was needed for the long trips. Earth exploited its coal and uranium with increasing efficiency, but there was only so much of both.\f0\par
But slowly Multivac learned enough to answer deeper questions more fundamentally, and on May 14, 2061, what had been theory, became fact.\par
\pard\sl-498\slmult0\qj\tx204 The energy of the sun was stored, converted, and utilized directly on a planet-wide scale. All Earth turned off its burning coal, its fissioning uranium, and flipped the switch that connected all of it to a small station, one mile in diameter, circling the Earth at half\f1  \f0 the distance of the Moon. All Earth ran by invisible beams of sun\-power.\par
\pard\fi397\sl-498\slmult0\qj\tx396 Seven days had not sufficed to dim the glory of it and Adell and Lupov finally managed to escape from the public function, and to meet in quiet where no one would think of looking for them, in the deserted underground chambers, where portions of the mighty buried body of Multivac showed. Unattended, idling, sorting data with contented lazy clickings, Multivac, too, had earned its vacation and the boss appreciated that. They had no intention, originally, of disturbing it.\par
They had brought a bottle with them, and their only concern at the moment was to relax in the company of each other and the bottle.\par
\f1 "It\rquote s amazing when you think of it,\rdblquote  said Adell. His broad face had lines of weariness in it, and he stirred his drink slowly with a glass rod, watching the cubes of ice slur clumsily about. \ldblquote All the energy we can possibly ever use for free. Enough energy, if we wanted to draw on it, to melt all Earth into a big drop of impure liquid iron, and still never \ul\f0 miss\ulnone\f1  the energy so used. All the energy we could ever use, forever and forever and forever.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 Lupov cocked his head sideways. He had a trick of doing that when he wanted to be contrary, kind he wanted to be contrary now, partly because he had had to carry the ice and glassware. \ldblquote Not forever,\rdblquote  he said.\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Oh, hell, just about forever. Till the sun runs down, Bert.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote That\rquote s not forever.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote All right, then. Billions and billions of years. Twenty billion, maybe. Are you satisfied?\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 Lupov put his fingers through his thinning hair as though to reassure himself that some was still left and sipped gently at his own drink. \ldblquote Twenty biffion years isn\rquote t forever.\rdblquote\f0\par
\pard\li386\qj\tx385\f1\ldblquote Well, it \i\f0 will \i0\f1 last our time, won\rquote t it?\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote So would the coal and uranium.\rdblquote\f0\par
\pard\fi397\sl-498\slmult0\qj\tx396\f2 "All right, \f1 but now we can hook up each individual spaceship to the Solar Station, and it can go to Pluto and back a million times without ever worrying about fuel. You can\rquote t do \i\f0 that \i0\f1 on coal and uranium. Ask Multivac, if you don\rquote t believe me.\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote I don\rquote t have to ask Multivac. I know that.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 "Then stop running down what Multivac\rquote s done for us,\rdblquote  said Adell, blazing up, \ldblquote It did all right.\rdblquote\par
\pard\fi408\sl-498\slmult0\tx408\cf1\ldblquote Who says it didn\rquote t? What I say is that a sun won\rquote t \f0 last \f1 forever. That\rquote s all I\rquote m \f2 saying. \f1 We\rquote re safe for twenty \f0 billion \f1 years; but then what\rquote  Lupov pointed a slightly shaky finger at the other. \f3\ldblquote And \f1 don\rquote t say we'll switch to another sun.\rdblquote\f0\par
There was silence for a while. Adell put his glass to his lips only occasionally, and Lupov's eyes slowly \f2 closed. \f0 They rested d.\par
\f1 Then Lupov\rquote s \f0 eyes \f1 snapped open. \ldblquote You\rquote re thinking we\rquote ll switch itch to another sun when ours is done, aren\rquote t you?\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\lquote Tm not thinking.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 "Sure you are. You\rquote re weak on logic, that\rquote s the trouble with you. You\rquote re like the guy in the story who was caught in a sudden shower and who \f0 ran \f1 to a grove of trees and got under one. He wasn\rquote t worried, you see, because he ligured when one tree got wet through, he would just \f4 get \f0 under another one.\par
\f1\ldblquote I get it,\rdblquote  said Adell. \lquote Don\rquote t shout. When the sun is done, the other stars \f0 will \f1 be gone, too.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Darn \f0 right \f1 they will,\rdblquote  muttered Lupov. \ldblquote It all had a beginning in the \f0 original cosmic explosion, whLitever that was, and it'll all have an end when all the stars run down. Some run \f1 dcwn faster than others. Hell, the giants won\rquote t last a hundred million years. The sun \f0 will last twenty billion years and maybe the dwarfs will last a hundred billion for all the good they are. But just give us a trillion years and everything will be dark. Entropy has to increase to max\-\f1 imum, that\rquote s all.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 "I know all about entropy,\rdblquote  said Adell, standing on \f0 his dignity.\par
\f1\ldblquote The hell you do.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote I know as much as you do.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Then you know everything\rquote s got to \f0 run \f1 down someday.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote All \f0 right. Who \f1 says they won\rquote t?\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\lquote You did, you \f0 poor sap. You said we had all the energy we needed, \f1 forever. You said \lquote forever.\rquote\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 It was Adell\rquote s turn to be contrary. \ldblquote Maybe we \f0 can \f1 build things up again someday,\rdblquote  he said.\f0\par
\f1 "Never.\rdblquote\f0\par
"Why not? Someday.\par
\f1\ldblquote Ask Multivac.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Never.\rdblquote\f0\par
\i\f1\ldblquote You \i0\f0 ask Multivac. I dare you. Five \f1 dollars says it can\rquote t be done.\rdblquote\f0\par
\pard\sl-243\slmult0\qj\tx204 Adell was just drunk enough to try, jut sober enough to be able\f1  \f5 to phrase the necessary symbols and operations into a question which, in words, might have corresponded to this: Will mankind one day without the net expenditure of energy be able to restore the sun to its full youthfulness even after it had died of old age?\par
\pard\fi210\sl-243\slmult0\qj\tx209 Or maybe it could be put more simply like this: How can the net amount of entropy of the universe be massively decreased?\par
Multivac fell dead and silent. The slow flashing of lights ceased, the distant sounds of clicking relays ended.\par
Then, just as the frightened technicians felt they could hold their breath no longer, there was a sudden springing to life of the teletype attached to that portion of Multivac. Five words were printed: In\f0\-\b\f5 SUFFICIENT DATA FOR MEANINGFUL ANSWER.\par
\pard\sl-243\slmult0\qj\tx209\par
\pard\fi210\sl-243\slmult0\qj\tx209\b0\ldblquote No bet,\rdblquote  whispered Lupov. They left hurriedly.\par
By next morning, the two, plagued with throbbing head and cottony mouth, had forgotten the incident.\par
\pard\sl-243\slmult0\qj\tx209\par
\pard\fi210\sl-243\slmult0\qj\tx209 Jerrodd, Jerrodine, and Jerrodette I and II watched the starry picture in the visiplate change as the passage through hyperspace was completed in its non-time lapse. At once, the even powdering of stars gave way to the predominance of a single bright marble-disk, centered.\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s X-23,\rdblquote  said Jerrodd confidently. His thin hands clamped tightly behind his back and the knuckles whitened.\par
The little Jerrodettes, both girls, had experienced the hyperspace passage for the first time in their lives and were self-conscious over the momentary sensation of inside-outness. They buried their giggles and chased one another wildly about their mother, screaming, \ldblquote We\rquote ve reached X-23-we\rquote ve reached X-23-we\rquote ve------\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Quiet, children,\rdblquote  said Jerrodine sharply. \ldblquote Are you sure, Jer\f0\-\f5 rodd?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What is there to be but sure?\rdblquote  asked Jerrodd, glancing up at the bulge of featureless metal just under the ceiling. It ran the length of the room, disappearing through the wall at either end. It was as long as the ship.\par
Jerrodd scarcely knew a thing about the thick rod of metal except that it was called a Microvac, that one asked it questions if one wished; that if one did not it still had its task of guiding the ship to a preordered destination; of feeding on energies from the various Sub-galactic Power Stations; of computing the equa\f0\-\f5 tions for the hyperspacial jumps.\par
\pard\fi221\sl-243\slmult0\qj\tx221\cf0\f0 Jerrodd and his family had only to wait and live in the com\-fortable residence quarters of the ship.\par
\f1 Someone had once told Jerrodd that the \ldblquote ac\rdblquote  at the end of \ldblquote Microvac\rdblquote  stood for \ldblquote analog computer\rdblquote  in ancient English, but he was on the edge of forgetting even that.\f0\par
\f1 Jerrodine\rquote s eyes were moist as she watched the visiplate. \ldblquote I can\rquote t help it. I feel funny about leaving Earth.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Why, for Pete\rquote s sake?\rdblquote  demanded Jerrodd. \ldblquote We had nothing there. We\rquote ll have everything on X-23. You won\rquote t be alone. You won\rquote t be a pioneer. There are over a million people on the planet already. Good Lord, our great-grandchildren will be looking for new worlds because X-23 will be overcrowded.\rdblquote  Then, after a re\f0\-\f1 flective pause, \ldblquote I tell you, it\rquote s a lucky thing the computers worked out interstellar travel the way the race is growing.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\lquote I know, I know,\rdblquote  said Jerrodine miserably.\f0\par
\f1 Jerrodette 1 said promptly, \ldblquote Our Microvac is the best Microvac in the world.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote I think so, too,\rdblquote  said Jerrodd, tousling her hair.\f0\par
It \i was \i0\f1 a nice feeling to have a Microvac of your own and Jerrodd was glad he was part of his generation and no other. In his father\rquote s youth, the only computers had been tremendous machines taking up a hundred square miles of land. There was only one to a planet. Planetary ACs they were called. They had been growing in size steadily for a thousand years and then, all at once, came refinement. In place of transistors, had come molecular valves so that even the largest Planetary AC could be put into a space only \f0 half the volume of a spaceship.\par
\f1 Jerrodd felt uplifted, as he always did when he thought that his own personal Microvac was many times more complicated than the ancient and primitive Multivac that had first tamed the Sun, and almost as complicated as Earth\rquote s Planetary AC (the largest) that had first solved the problem of hyperspatial travel and had made trips to the stars possible.\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote So many stars, so many planets,\rdblquote  sighed Jerrodine, busy with her own thoughts. \ldblquote I suppose families will be going out to new planets forever, the way we are now.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Not forever,\rdblquote  said Jerrodd, with a smile. \ldblquote It will all stop some\f0\-\f1 day, but not for billions of years. Many billions. Even the stars run down, you know. Entropy must increase.\rdblquote\f0\par
\pard\fi397\sl-498\slmult0\qj\tx396\f1\ldblquote What\rquote s entropy, daddy?\rdblquote  shrilled Jerrodette \b\f0 II.\par
\pard\fi210\sl-238\slmult0\tx209\b0\f1\ldblquote Entropy, little sweet, is just a word which means the amount of running-down of the universe. Everything runs down, you know, like your little walkie-talkie robot, remember?\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Can\rquote t you just put in a new power-unit, like with my robot?\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote The stars \i\f0\fs20 are \i0\f1\fs22 the power-units, dear. Once they\rquote re gone, there are no more power-units.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 Jerrodette I at once set up a howl. \ldblquote Don\rquote t let them, daddy. Don\rquote t let the stars run down.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Now look what you\rquote ve done,\rdblquote  whispered Jerrodine, exasperated. \ldblquote How was I to know it would frighten them?\rdblquote  Jerrodd whispered back.\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Ask the Microvac,\rdblquote  wailed Jerrodette I. \ldblquote Ask him bow to turn the stars on again.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Go ahead,\rdblquote  said Jerrodine. \ldblquote It wifi quiet them down.\rdblquote  (Jerro\f0\-dette II was beginning to cry, also).\par
\f1 Jerrodd shrugged. \ldblquote Now, now, honeys. \f6 I\rquote ll \f1 ask Microvac. Don\rquote t worry, he\rquote ll tell us.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 He asked the Microvac, adding quickly, \ldblquote Print the answer.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 Jerrodd cupped the strip of thin cellufilm and said cheerfully, \ldblquote See now, the Microvac says it will take care of everything when the time comes so don\rquote t worry.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 Jerrodine said, \ldblquote And now, children, it\rquote s time for bed. We\rquote ll be in our new home soon.\rdblquote\f0\par
Jerrodd read the words on the celluflim again before destroying\par
\pard\tx204 it: \b\fs16 INSUFFICIENT DATA FOR MEANINGFUL ANSWER.\par
\par
\pard\fi210\sl-238\slmult0\tx209\b0\fs22 He shrugged and looked at the visiplate. X-23 was just ahead.\par
