\pard\fi210\sl-238\slmult0\tx209\f1 VJ-23X of Lameth stared into the black depths of the three-dimensional, small-scale map of the Galaxy and said, \ldblquote Are we ridicu\f0\-\f1 lous, I wonder, in being so concerned about the matter?\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 MQ-17J of Nicron shook his head. \ldblquote I think not. You know the Galaxy will be filled in five years at the present rate of expansion.\rdblquote\f0\par
Both seemed in their early twenties, both were tall and perfectly formed.\par
\f1\ldblquote Still,\rdblquote  said VJ-23X, \ldblquote I hesitate to submit a pessimistic report to the Galactic Council.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote I wouldn\rquote t consider any other kind of report. Stir them up a bit. We\rquote ve got to stir them up.\rdblquote\f0\par
\pard\fi397\sl-498\slmult0\qj\tx396\f1 VJ-23X sighed. \ldblquote Space is infinite. A hundred billion Galaxies are there for the taking. More.\rdblquote\par
\pard\fi210\sl-249\slmult0\qj\tx209\b\ldblquote A hundred billion is \b0\i\f7\fs20 not \i0\f1\fs22 infinite and it\rquote s getting less infinite all the tune. Consider! Twenty thousand years ago, mankind first solved the problem of utilizing stellar energy, and a few centuries later, interstellar travel became possible. it took mankind a million years to fill one small world and then only fifteen thousand years to fill the rest of the Galaxy. Now the populauon doubles every \f0\fs20 ten \f1\fs22 years-\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 VJ-23X interrupted. \ldblquote We can thank immortality for that.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Very well. Immortality exists and we have to take it into account. I admit it has its seamy side, this immortality. The Galactic AC has solved many problems for us, but in solving the problem of preventing old age and death, it has undone all its other solutions.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Yet you wouldn\rquote t want to abandon life, I suppose.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Not at all,\rdblquote  snapped MQ-17J, softening it at once to, \ldblquote Not yet. I\rquote m by no means old enough. How old are you?\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Two hundred twenty-three. And you?\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote I\rquote m still under two hundred. -But to get back to my point. Population doubles every ten years. Once this Galaxy is filled, we\rquote ll have filled another in ten years. Another ten years and we\rquote ll have filled two more. Another decade, four more. In a hundred years, we\rquote ll have filled a thousand Galaxies. In a thousand years, a million Galaxies. In ten thousand years, the entire known Universe. Then what?\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 VJ-23X said, \ldblquote As a side issue, there\rquote s a problem of transporta\f0\-tion. I wonder how many sunpower units it will take to move Gal\-\f1 axies of individuals from one Galaxy to the next.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote A very good point. Already, mankind consumes two sunpower units per year.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Most of it\rquote s wasted. After all, our own Galaxy alone pours out a thousand sunpower units a year and we only use two of those.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Granted, but even with a hundred per cent efficiency, we only stave off the end. Our energy requirements are going up in a geometric progression even faster than our population. We\rquote ll run out of energy even sooner than we run out of Galaxies. A good point. A very good point.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote We\rquote ll just have to build new stars out of interstellar gas.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Or out of dissipated heat?\rdblquote  asked MQ-171, sarcastically.\f0\par
\pard\fi397\sl-498\slmult0\qj\tx396\f1\ldblquote There may be \b\f0 some way to reverse entropy. We ought to \b0 ask the Galactic \b\f1 AC.\rdblquote\par
\pard\fi199\sl-238\slmult0\qj\tx198\f0 VJ-23X \b0 was not really serious, but MQ-17J pulled out his AC-contact from his pocket and placed it on the table before him.\par
\f1\ldblquote I\rquote ve half a mind to,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote It\rquote s something the human race will have to face someday.\rdblquote\f0\par
He stared somberly at his small AC-contact. It was only two inches cubed and nothing in itself, but it was connected through hyperspace with the great Galactic AC that served all mankind. Hyperspace considered, it was an integral part of the Galactic AC.\par
MQ-17J paused to wonder if someday in his immortal life he would get to see the Galactic AC. It was on a little world of its own, a spider webbing of force-beams holding the matter within which surges of sub-mesons took the place of the old clumsy molecular valves. Yet despite its sub-etheric workings, the Galactic AC was known to be a full thousand feet across.\par
\f1 MQ-17J asked suddenly of his AC-contact, \ldblquote Can entropy ever be reversed?\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 VJ-23X looked startled and said at once, \ldblquote Oh, say, I didn\rquote t really mean to have you ask that.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote We both know entropy can\rquote t be reversed. You can\rquote t turn smoke and ash back into a tree.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Do you have trees on your world?\rdblquote  asked MQ-17J.\f0\par
The sound of the Galactic AC startled them into silence. Its voice came thin and beautiful out of the small AC-contact on the desk. It said: \b\fs16 THERE IS INSUFFICIENT DATA FOR A MEANINGFUL ANSWER.\par
\pard\sl-238\slmult0\qj\tx198\par
\pard\fi199\sl-238\slmult0\qj\tx198\b0\f1\fs22 VJ-23X said, \ldblquote See!\rdblquote\f0\par
The two men thereupon returned to the question of the report they were to make to the Galactic Council.\par
