\pard\fi199\sl-238\slmult0\qj\tx198\f1 Zee Prime\rquote s mind spanned the new Galaxy with a faint interest in the countless twists of stars that powdered it. He had never seen this one before. Would he ever see them all? So many of them, each with its load of humanity. -But a load that was almost a dead weight. More and more, the real essence of men was to be found out here, in space.\f0\par
\pard\sl-238\slmult0\qj\tx204 Minds, not bodies! The immortal bodies remained back on the planets, in suspension over the eons. Sometimes they roused for material activity but that was growing rarer. Few new individuals were coming into existence to join the incredibly mighty throng,\f1  \f0 but what matter? There was little room in the Universe for new individuals.\par
\pard\fi216\sl-238\slmult0\qj\tx215 Zee Prime was roused out of his reverie upon coming across the wispy tendrils of another mind.\par
\f1\ldblquote I am Zee Prime,\rdblquote  said Zee Prime. \ldblquote And you?\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote I am Dee Sub Wun. Your Galaxy?\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote We call it only the Galaxy. And you?\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote We call ours the same. All men call their Galaxy their Galaxy and nothing more. Why not?\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote True. Since all Galaxies are the same.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Not all Galaxies. On one particular Galaxy the race of man must have originated. That makes it different.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 Zee Prime said, \ldblquote On which one?\rdblquote\f0\par
\b\f1\ldblquote I \b0 cannot say. The Universal AC would know.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Shall we ask him? I am suddenly curious.\rdblquote\f0\par
\f1 Zee Prime\rquote s perceptions broadened until the Galaxies themselves shrank and became a new, more diffuse powdering on a much larger background. So many hundreds of billions of them, all with their immortal beings, aLl carrying their load of inteffigences with minds that drifted freely through space. And yet one of them was unique among them all in being the original Galaxy. One of them had, in its vague and distant past, a period when it was the only Galaxy populated by man.\f0\par
\f1 Zee Prime was consumed with curiosity to see this Galaxy and he called out: \ldblquote Universal AC! On which Galaxy did mankind origi\f0\-\f1 nate?\rdblquote\f0\par
The Universal AC heard, for on every world and throughout space, it had its receptors ready, and each receptor lead through hyperspace to some unknown point where the Universal AC kept itself aloof.\par
Zee Prime knew of only one man whose thoughts had penetrated within sensing distance of Universal AC, and he reported only a shining globe, two feet across, difficult to see.\par
\f1\ldblquote But how can that be all of Universal AC?\rdblquote  Zee Prime had asked.\f0\par
\f1\ldblquote Most of it,\rdblquote  had been the answer, \ldblquote is in hyperspace. In what form it is there I cannot imagine.\rdblquote\f0\par
Nor could anyone, for the day had long since passed, Zee Prime knew, when any man had any part of the making of a Universal AC. Each Universal AC designed and constructed its successor.\par
\pard\sl-243\slmult0\tx204 Each, during its existence of a million years or more accumulated the necessary data to build a better and more intricate, more capable successor in which its own store of data and individuality would be submerged.\par
The Universal AC interrupted Zee \f1 Prime\rquote s wandering thoughts, not with words, but \f0 with \f1 guidance. Zee Prune\rquote s mentality \f0 was guided into the dim sea of Galaxies and one in particular enlarged into stars.\par
A thought came, infinitely distant, but infinitely clear. \f1\fs16\ldblquote THIS IS \f7 THE \f0 ORIGINAL GALAXY \f1 OF MAN.\rdblquote\f0\par
\par
\fs22 But it was the same after all, the same as any other, and Zee Prime stifled his disappointment.\par
Dee Sub Wun, whose mind had accompanied \f1 the other, said suddenly, \ldblquote And is one of \f0 these stars the original \f1 star of Man?\rdblquote\f0\par
\pard\fi204\sl-238\slmult0\tx204 The Universal AC said, \f1\fs16\ldblquote MAN\rquote S ORIGINAL STAR HAS GONE \f0 NOVA. IT IS A WHITE \f1 DWARF.\rdblquote\f0\par
\pard\sl-238\slmult0\tx204\par
\pard\fi210\sl-243\slmult0\tx209\f1\fs22\ldblquote Did \f0 the men upon it \f1 die?\rdblquote  asked Zee Prime, startled and \f0 without thinking.\par
\pard\fi204\sl-243\slmult0\tx204 The Universal AC said, \f1\fs16\ldblquote A \f0 NEW WORLD, AS IN SUCH CASES WAS CONSTRUCTED FOR \f1 THEIR PHYSICAL BODIES IN TIME.\rdblquote\f0\par
\pard\sl-243\slmult0\tx204\par
\f1\fs22\ldblquote Yes, of course,\rdblquote  said Zee Prime, but a sense of loss overwhelmed him even so. His \f0 mind released its hold on the original Galaxy of Man, let it spring back and lose itself among the blurred pin points. He never wanted to see it again.\par
